sa(dp248
g2
V"Guardians of the Galaxy" relied too much on the audience already knowing the Marvel mythology. Call it, in my opinion, an unacceptable shorthand.
p249
sg4
V Yes, we should.\u201d CGI effects create two central characters in \u201cGuardians of the Galaxy.\u201d\u000aAre you making \u201cGuardians of the Galaxy\u201d for Marvel Comics fans? Or, do you want everyone to come along for the ride? I asked myself those questions and more during a promotional screening of this sure-to-be late summer hit. The answers left me less than impressed. What distinguishes a great adaptation from a mediocre film is its ability to stand apart from the source material. \u201cGuardians of the Galaxy\u201d relied too much on the audience already knowing the Marvel mythology. Call it, in my opinion, an unacceptable shorthand. The filmmakers substituted mindless action for a good fleshing-out of the story. \u201cGalaxy\u201d opens with the reasonably touching scene of a boy losing his mother to cancer. The kid has trouble saying goodbye to his mom on her deathbed and instead retreats to his \u201cSony Walkman\u201d mix tape of hits from the 1970\u2019s. Cut to 26 years later and the exploits of a Han Solo/Indiana Jones hybrid out to steal a mysterious orb from an alien planet. We learn very little about the central character, Peter Quill (Chris Pratt). Just go with it, right? He\u2019s a righteous space dude who loves 70\u2019s music. Yeah, that\u2019s it. We also learn precious little about the other characters who unite to become the \u201cGuardians of the Galaxy.\u201d A few lines of dialogue for each principal. Sorry. No time, folks. We have at least a dozen villains you need to meet. The story overflows with characters, all vying for a big onscreen moment. The cast is pretty good, actually. Pratt brings a goofball charm to his Han Solo clone. Zoe Saldana goes from the blue makeup of \u201cAvatar\u201d to the amazingly different green makeup of Gamora. Uh, okay. Dave Bautista wasn\u2019t bad as Drax the Destroyer, a space alien who only understands literal references (similar to Spock in \u201cStar Trek.\u201d) Vin Diesel (box office poison for any movie that doesn\u2019t have the word \u201cfast\u201d in the title) supplies the voice of Groot, a tree-like humanoid. Bradley Cooper provides the comic relief as Rocket, a genetically modified raccoon. The villains are such generic comic-book stereotypes, I won\u2019t even bother mentioning. On the positive side, the film has an above-average sense of humor. The talking raccoon was amusing at times, but annoying at other times. A few of the special effects shots were impressive. But, they often crowded the story. Less is more sometimes. The 3D conversion was also above average. On the negative side, why wasn\u2019t there more of an original score? I realize Quill enjoys his 70\u2019s music. And, personally, it\u2019s my favorite decade. But, it\u2019s lazy to let established pop hits of decades past to stand in for first-rate original music. Music should help tell the story. Established hit singles bring too much baggage. Despite what I might think of the finished product, \u201cGuardians of the Galaxy\u201d will be a huge box office hit. And, it will likely break August box office records. As mindless fun, it works.  
p250
sa(dp251
g2
VIt's preposterous, ridiculous, bizarre. Whatever. It's not the most accessible Marvel outing, and it'll take the fanboys to spread the word; Guardians of the Galaxy is balls-out fun.
p252
sg4
VIf one were to take a step back \u000afrom the Marvel franchise and consider, for one moment, precisely how \u000asilly the entire concept of costumed superheroes is, one might realise \u000athat, beneath the blockbuster exteriors, those majestic CGI explosions \u000aand Sam Jackson eyepieces, the studio rely rather heavily on comic book \u000afandom to keep it all going. \u000aAs hard as it might be to believe, you ain't seen nothing \u000ayet. Guardians of the Galaxy takes Marvel's inherent silliness, cranks \u000ait up to 11 and wears it like a cape. \u000aIt's a movie about a genetically altered racoon with a bad\u000a attitude. A walking tree that speaks but three words. And a central \u000ahero who calls himself Star Lord (although nobody else will join him in\u000a doing so). \u000aFor a studio obsessed with such a cookie cutter, \u000aplanned-out approach, the idea that Marvel will take their universe and \u000aturn it on its head in such a manner is either brave or foolhardy. Or \u000aperhaps both. \u000aPeter (Pratt) is a human, taken from Earth at a young age \u000aand raised by 'Ravagers' from a distant planet. He's a chancer and a \u000acad. A Han Solo for the age. He hunts for loot and tries to sell it, \u000awhich is why he's on a remote planet collecting an orb, which he hopes \u000ato trade for a hefty fee. \u000aBut this is no ordinary orb (if ever such a thing \u000aexisted). This is an orb that contains the power to destroy entire \u000aplanets. Which is why uber villain Thanos (an uncredited Josh Brolin) \u000aand his right hand man Ronan (Pace) are so desperate to get their hands \u000aon it. \u000aSo the villains send Gamora (Saldana) to retrieve it from \u000aPeter, little knowing that she has an agenda of her own. And also that \u000athe talking racoon and walking tree are hoping to get in on the act \u000a(it's a bit of a Solo/ Chewbecca double act). \u000aWith the quartet getting into a scrape, and subsequently \u000alocked up in a maximum security prison where they meet Drax the \u000aDestroyer (Bautista), they begin to realise that in order to achieve \u000acommon goals (from getting out of prison to saving the galaxy), they're \u000agoing to need each other. \u000aAnd that's largely the theme of the movie. Against a \u000abackdrop of increasing stupidity (the names of characters and locations \u000agenerally start with the letter Z and sound as though they came from the\u000a imagination of a small child), the character relationships somehow hold\u000a it all together. That and some excellent comic timing. \u000aMuch of the script is dedicated to making the audience \u000alaugh. Tension is largely built up in order to deliver a chuckle, rather\u000a than a scare. With licence to curse and a touch more violence to \u000aproceedings than most of the Avengers can muster, there's an edge to \u000athis one. \u000aChris Pratt does a remarkable job of maintaing the charm \u000aand vulnerability of the lead role, and Saldana also offers her acting \u000achops to make Gomora a believable ass-kicker with far more depth than, \u000asay, Scarlett Johannson's Black Widow.\u000aBut, and this is the major surprise, it's Rocket Racoon \u000aand his muscle man Groot that provide the most fun and even intrigue. \u000aDirector Gunn has a whale of a time dialling up the ridiculous, not \u000aleast with these two CG creations who offer a plethora of options for \u000aset pieces and one liners. \u000aJohn C. Reilly turns up as a prison warden, doing his \u000astandard John C Reilly thing, and there's a certain irony in Glenn Close\u000a looking bewildered by the tone. While she pitches for slapstick \u000asilliness, the rest of the cast play it earnestly enough to make those \u000aone liners, those mumbled, stuttering one liners that have become \u000aAmerican comedy staple, that much more humour. \u000aIt does look like a Satruday morning cartoon. It's \u000apreposterous, ridiculous, bizarre. Whatever. It's not the most \u000aaccessible Marvel outing, and it'll take the fanboys to spread the word;\u000a Guardians of the Galaxy is balls-out fun
