g2
VThe best thriller of the year. And then some.
p524
sg4
VOnce upon a time Amy and Nick Dunne (Affleck and Pike) were the perfect couple. Both successful writers, they lived the New York high-life from their DINKY brownstone and weren't averse to a quick knee-trembler between the shelves of their local bookstore.Five years on and things aren't looking so good. Both now redundant, they've blown Amy's trust fund on a bar in the Missouri boondocks of Nick's hometown Grand Carthage and they irritably rattle around a clapboard house that is too big for them. Then Amy disappears.Local cop Kim Dickens dutifully investigates and intuits a lack of concern from Nick, a suspicion that soon appears well-founded as forensics turn up a hastily cleaned-up crime scene at the house, a massive credit card splurge on man toys and the suggestion that Amy was fearing for her life.Nick insists he knows nothing...but his smug appearance at a press conference, the ire of local friends of Amy he never knew she had and trial-by-cable-television from a particularly prurient network all work against his protestations even before his infidelity with a young student is revealed. As he readily admits, he's become "the most hated man in America". But is he guilty?Novelist-turned-screenwriter Gillian Flynn hasn't majorly altered the plot of her best-selling novel but she has tightened it up, dispensing minor characters with a dramatic shorthand, while David Fincher is the perfect director to explore the time-shifting complications of the original.Affleck is superb, his nuanced portrayal of a metropolitan alpha male reduced to provincial impotence making him the ideal sucker to play fall guy to the Machiavellian machinations of a good wife turned bad. But, then again, he's exactly the type of man to murderously resent the disappointment of a wife who's bankrolling his latest failure.It's a terrific performance yet the greatest revelation is Bond girl-turned-gone girl Pike - always good for minor roles in Pride & Prejudice and An Education - but here coolly revelling in a multi-layered role that requires both strength and subtlety as what appeared a straightforward police procedural morphs into darker beast altogether.Around them Tyler Perry almost makes you forgive him for his soft soap rom-coms as a media savvy lawyer who's slick championing of Nick's cause nudges along the plot trajectory while his ultra-loyal sister Margo (Carrie Coon) provides a beacon of sanity even as the case against her feckless brother towers over him.It's a mesmerising ride that's confident enough to find room for some welcome gallows humour, particularly after a game-changing switcheroo at the half-way mark which propels the action into a deeper, darker direction completely.The best thriller of the year. And then some
p525
