g2
VA bombast-and-crisis megamovie, rocket-fuelled by gobbledygeek. The pummelling of plot turns and ratcheting of emotion-wrenches rarely relent. Forgets that we mere humans don't yet possess infinite patience for hyper-epic hokum.
p571
sg4
V \u000aIn 1968, when Stanley Kubrick\u2019s 2001: A Space Odyssey was released, on 70 mm and in a 2.21:1 aspect ratio, it would be another year before Apollo 11 landed on the moon. That spectacle was small-screen\u2014broadcast live, in grainy black-and-white to TVs back on Earth, Neil Armstrong took \u201cone giant leap for mankind,\u201d ending the Space Race. But by 1979, the $500-million-plus grossed planet-wide for George Lucas\u2019 $11-million space opera signalled the launch of Hollywood\u2019s Blockbuster Race. Ever since, we\u2019ve had soaring, FX-engineered spectacles on NASA-level budgets taking us far, far away. These unearthly epics, charting a meteoric course to the top of the box office, are fitted with marketing rocket-boosters, piloted by A-list stars, and boast more of a stratospheric emotional arc than any space agency\u2019s plotted in decades. For a super-sized-movie\u2019s director, it\u2019s all about mission control. Christopher Nolan, who in 1998 made his feature debut with black-and-white neo-noir Following (budget: $6000), has become a go-to populist auteur for blockbusters. He\u2019s earned such a banked-on reputation for delivering huge films under budget that, in an unprecedented deal, Warner Bros traded rights to two franchises and a property to-be-determined to Paramount (the project\u2019s initiator and owners of the script, by Nolan\u2019s brother Jonathan) to secure international distribution for Interstellar (budget: $165 million). But Nolan\u2019s 2001 for 2014 lacks story control. From its earworm-hole of a score (in climactic moments, Hans Zimmer\u2019s music even overwhelms the dialogue) to its warped drive through plots\u2014secret hideout-discovery, code breaking, father-daughter drama, traitor-among-us suspense, sci-fi salvation\u2014Interstellar is a bombast-and-crisis megamovie, rocket-fuelled by gobbledygeek. The dominant force here is love\u2014a re-romanticization of NASA, then a stars-spanning swoon into the notion that love\u2019s a human force as great as gravity. Seriously. (The great threat isn\u2019t machine, as in 2001, but isolated, loveless man.) Cooper (Matthew McConaughey), once a shuttle pilot, lives in a farmhouse with daughter Murphy and son Tom; the Earth\u2019s plagued by dust storms and blight. Cooper\u2019s drawn back to NASA (don\u2019t ask), where Dr Brand (Michael Caine) wants him to fly through a wormhole to a system with planets that may prove inhabitable. The mission dwindles quickly from exploration into survival (it makes Gravity\u2018s obstacle-course seem banally believable). Cooper remains a cerebral super-man throughout, an ever-staunch starfighter coming up with brilliant, humanity-saving ideas in no time; colleague Amelia Brand (Anne Hathaway) mostly shoulders blame and harbours a secret love. There is a brilliant sequence imagining time and memory as its own dimension\u2014a colour-and-light-striated infinite hall of bookcases. Grainy video-feeds of Murphy, all grown up (Jessica Chastain) and talking to Cooper from years away (because of relativity and blahblackholeblah) are deeply moving. But the pummelling of plot turns and ratcheting of emotion-wrenches rarely relent; a flurry of crises melts into a wash of ideas about space-time that would have even Dr Who over his head. Less propaganda for space-flight than flashy, overstuffed advertising for the dimension-smashing abilities of blockbuster-moviemaking itself\u2014watch as heart and mind, space and time, past and present, are rolled into one incandescent ball of supernova sensation there on the event-horizon!\u2014Interstellar, arcing on and on and on for 165 minutes, forgets that we mere humans don\u2019t yet possess infinite patience for hyper-epic hokum.
p572
sa(dp573
g2
VWith its intellectually stimulating ideas and profound emotional ballast, Interstellar makes a solid impact, albeit without the Wow Factor
p574
sg4
VConceptually brilliant, Christopher Nolan's epic sci-fi drama is all about time. Time - as the world's most valuable commodity, and in short supply - like the Earth's food. But it is also the enemy
