VRichly detailed and labyrinthinely plotted, the switchback narrative is populated with carefully delineated characters without recourse to cumbersome exposition.
p660
sg4
VThe "missing child" thriller staple is given a glacially serpentine twist in this first-rate suspenser from Canadian director Denis Villeneuve.\u000a\u000aThe set-up is simple - God-fearing carpenter Keller Dover (Jackman) and his family join neighbour Franklin Birth (Terrence Howard) and his brood for Thanksgiving dinner.\u000a\u000aHowever, the conviviality of their get-together descends into an atmosphere of icy dread when their two young daughters Anna and Joy go outside to play...and disappear.\u000a\u000aCrazed with worry, Keller and Franklin search the streets while police officer Loki (Gyllenhaal), a cop with a 100% success rate, is summoned.\u000a\u000aLocal man Alex Jones (Dano), a learning-impaired misfit, is quickly fingered as the culprit...but Loki is forced to let him go due to lack of forensic evidence and an inconclusive polygraph.\u000a\u000aKeller, who remains unconvinced as the suspected abductor was spotted in the area and had fled when police were trying to make an arrest, accosts Loki outside the police station, claiming he heard Jones say "They only cried when I left them." \u000a\u000aConvinced of the man's guilt, Keller embarks on a grim revenge mission while Loki's own investigation into local sex offenders opens up another sordid avenue of inquiry.\u000a\u000aRichly detailed and labyrinthinely plotted, the switchback narrative is populated with carefully delineated characters without recourse to cumbersome exposition.\u000a\u000aWe learn little about Loki, although Villeneuve supplies just enough information - DIY tattoos, an air of desolate intensity - to let us get the measure of the man while Keller is a seething bundle of Old Testament certainties, his machismo dented by a failing business and inability to look after his family.\u000a\u000aGyllenhaal and Jackman have never been better, delivering nuanced performances that put tired flesh on the bones of their characters while serving a plot that pitches in unexpected directions, building to a sublimely tense, almost unwatchable, climax.\u000a\u000aOne the best films of the year
