VFollowing its inspirational introduction, the second chapter of the \u000adragon wranglers' handbook continues to pique the interest by putting \u000aits principles into splendidly illustrated practice.With the island of Berk now a model of Viking-dragon relations, young\u000a adventurer Hiccup (Jay Baruchel) is keen to put grown-up \u000aresponsibilities on hold while he explores the world with his trusty \u000aserpent steed Toothless.But as the son of big chieftain Stoick (Gerard Butler), expectations weigh heavy on his shoulders - and his one remaining foot.His leadership skills are duly tested when a long-forgotten thorn in \u000aStoick's side - the vengeful dragon master Drago (Djimon Hounsou) - \u000areturns with a scorched-earth approach to world domination.Anxious to stop Drago from turning dragon against dragon (and human, obviously), Hiccup sets out to bargain for peace.Already a diplomatic nightmare, his mission is further complicated by\u000a a crew of dragon-trappers led by the boneheaded Eret (Harington) and \u000athe appearance of an ethereal dragon rider whose identity comes as a \u000ahuge surprise... to anyone who hasn't seen the trailer.This blast from the past takes place on what's essentially the island\u000a twin of Avatar's Pandora, where dragons roam free and the Cate \u000aBlanchett-voiced rider, Valka, slinks around like the last remaining \u000aNa'vi.For a hermit, Valka is a terrible show off. But then this is a world \u000aof curiosities, such as how Drago is able to control the minds of \u000adragons simply by bellowing loudly and making circles with a big stick, \u000aand why the younger generation of Berk all sound as though they were \u000araised on the opposite side of the Atlantic to their parents (alas, \u000aHiccup still hasn't outgrown his nasal Canadian drawl).However, as the inevitable confrontations come to pass, the movie \u000acouldn't make its big messages any clearer. The evils of tyranny and \u000aoppression are boldly addressed. Bolder still, not everyone gets to live\u000a happily ever after.But the seriousness never lasts long while ever Stoick's old mate \u000aGobber (Craig Ferguson) and Hiccup's fellow dragoneers are around \u000a(voiced as they are by the likes of Jonah Hill, Kristen Wiig and \u000aChristopher Mintz-Plasse).One dramatic twist aside, the script tends to the derivative. A few \u000aof the action setpieces have a distinctly borrowed feel, beginning with a\u000a dragon race that looks like Quidditch with sheep before moving into \u000aAvatar territory and restaging key battles from the original Star Wars \u000atrilogy (baby dragons being the new Ewoks).What really impresses is how it all looks. The attention to detail is\u000a impeccable, from the showboating sweep of the aerial sequences to the \u000ainteractions and mannerisms of man, woman and beast.Textures and gestures are brilliantly rendered, the body language \u000asaying more about the characters and their relationships than any words,\u000a particularly between Hiccup and his leathery best friend - and his \u000afeisty girlfriend Astrid (America Ferrara).With 12 books in Cressida Cowell's best-selling series, there are \u000aplenty more exercises to come. The challenge is now to match the \u000astorytelling standards of the first with the animation of the second. \u000aPractice makes perfect
