V\u000aInfernal Affairs is a surprise; it\u2019s not the usual Hong Kong chop socky, but a thoughtful, well constructed police/crime drama with a well developed inner core that gives the story extra bite. The two opposites, both leading double lives, are connected by the sinew of lies they have to live, but their parallel lives also adds a certain bond that finally gives the film its pathos. \u000a\u000aAndy Lau\u2019s polished direction includes a few stylish flourishes, the dialogue is crisp and the edgy dynamics make this an audience pleaser. Characters, on both sides of the good/bad divide, are developed enough to make them more than graphic elements to fill scenes, and low key romantic / domestic asides give the film more depth. \u000a\u000aThe multi-talented and popular Lau and Tony Leung (fondly remembered by anyone who saw In The Mood For Love) both deliver first class performances that go beyond the usual stereotypes of police dramas; they add vulnerability and internal tension to their characters. The supports are all excellent, too.\u000a\u000aThe film tops and tails with a quotation about longevity not being an advantage in hell \u2013 and the film\u2019s focused storyline bears this out. While it has plenty of gutsy scenes, the film reaches wider with its attention to the humanity of its central characters. The film\u2019s enormous success in Hong Kong suggests that audiences can appreciate a film with more than 20 fight sequences going for it.\u000a
