VThe period details and zeitgeist echoes--along with one bravura sequence--make this another entertaining entry, though this rebooted, revised and repopulated franchise is starting to see diminishing returns.
p752
sg4
V \u000aX-Men: Days of Future Past is less a continuation of Marvel\u2019s mutant series than a sequel to the early \u201960s-set X-Men: First Class, where distrust of homo sapiens superior nestled into American history, right at home among Cold War paranoia. Here, the main storyline in a time-travel tale sees Magneto\u2019s pro-war (against humans) stance and Professor Xavier\u2019s pro-peace position face off in the early \u201970s, just as the Vietnam War is about to end. The period details and zeitgeist echoes\u2014along with one bravura sequence\u2014make this another entertaining entry, though this rebooted, revised and repopulated franchise is starting to see diminishing returns. Stuffed with mutants, particularly in the framing storyline\u2014set in a near future time, all doomy and gloomy and pretty uninteresting, when adaptive robot Sentinels scour the globe, eradicating super-humans\u2014this blockbuster only really gets going when Wolverine (Hugh Jackman) travels back to Nixon\u2019s US to convince a young Xavier (James McAvoy) and Magneto (Michael Fassbender) to help him stop Mystique (Jennifer Lawrence) from killing the Sentinel-inventing Bolivar Trask (Peter Dinklage). The murder would ensure that his creations launch their mutant-genocide decades later. The break-out of Magneto is the movie\u2019s high-point, capped by a deliciously playful, slo-mo fast-guy sequence\u2014to the tune of Jim Croce\u2019s \u201972 ditty \u201cTime in a Bottle\u201d\u2014featuring Quicksilver (Evan Peters). There are other deft touches, too: a Beast-ly allusion, in Paris, to Victor Hugo\u2019s Hunchback of Notre-Dame; bystanders\u2019 Super 8 footage of mutant battles; mutants\u2019 ironic musings on time as \u201cimmutable\u201d or not\u2014if Wolverine must go back to convince Xavier to be the man he is already in Wolverine\u2019s future, is that an argument for cosmic fate or for supremely human free will? Of course, if all this seems rather silly and comic-book geeky, it is. But there\u2019s the paradox of our sci-fi-, fantasy- and superhero- dominated movie-present (and serious Brit-thespians Patrick Stewart and Ian McKellen, appearing in the doomy future part, blur these genres here, their roles little different from their turns as Captain Picard or Gandalf, respectively), which X-M: DFP freeze-frames perfectly. The more specific, humorous, and human the details, the faster time will pass in yet another story of a future human, non-human, or adamantium-clawed, self-healing, cigar-smoking X-Man.
